Using Vieta's formulas, we know \( z_1 + z_2 = c \) and \( z_1 z_2 = 10 \). The roots are complex conjugates, so their product is 10, and their sum is \( c \). The vertices of the quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \) are \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \). Since \( z_1 \) and \( z_2 \) are complex conjugates, their reciprocals \( \frac{1}{z_1} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \) are also complex conjugates. We use the shoelace formula to calculate the area of the quadrilateral formed by these points. The coordinates of the vertices are: 1. \( z_1 = (a, b) \) 2. \( z_2 = (a, -b) \) 3. \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \left( \frac{a}{10}, \frac{b}{10} \right) \) 4. \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \left( \frac{a}{10}, -\frac{b}{10} \right) \) Applying the shoelace formula, we find the area to be \( \frac{81ab}{100} \). Using \( a = \frac{c}{2} \) and \( b = \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \), we express the area as a function of \( c \): \[ \text{Area} = \frac{81}{200} c \sqrt{10 - \frac{c^2}{4}} \] To maximize this area, we set \( t = c^2 \) and find the maximum value of \( \sqrt{10t - \frac{t^2}{4}} \). The maximum occurs at \( t = 20 \), leading to \( c = \sqrt{20} \). Therefore, \( c = \sqrt{m} \) implies \( m = 20 \). The value of \( m \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
